            <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><strong>1. Ask the teacher to keep the windows open as much as possible.</strong></p><p><strong>2. If there is a HEPA filter in the classroom…</strong></p><p>…ask the teacher to move it closer to the center of the room and run it as fast as possible (noise permitting).</p><p><strong>3. Ask the teacher if they can check the ventilation themselves</strong></p><h3>Joey Fox on Twitter: &quot;3 WAYS YOU CAN CHECK VENTILATION YOURSELFBefore checking, you need to find where the air is coming from. It&#39;s usually from a rectangular, circular or linear diffuser, or from a grill. Usually on the ceiling, but sometimes on a wall. Here are some examples.1/7 pic.twitter.com/vlTks1qQ17 / Twitter&quot;</h3><p>3 WAYS YOU CAN CHECK VENTILATION YOURSELFBefore checking, you need to find where the air is coming from. It&#39;s usually from a rectangular, circular or linear diffuser, or from a grill. Usually on the ceiling, but sometimes on a wall. Here are some examples.1/7 pic.twitter.com/vlTks1qQ17</p><p><strong>4. Get your kid a respirator.</strong></p><p>We get ours from <a href="https://cangardcare.com/product-category/respiratory-protection/kids-mask-respiratory-protection/">Cangard</a> because they have nice designs and my kids like them</p><p>Here are other Canadian manufacturers: <a href="https://cappem.ca/disposable-respirators">https://cappem.ca/disposable-respirators</a></p><p><strong>5. Tiny USB HEPA filter for their desk</strong></p><p>Maybe <a href="https://walmart.ca/en/ip/Mini-Portable-Air-Purifier-H13-True-HEPA-Filter-Travel-Size-Purifiers-Car-Baby-Stroller-Desktop-Dual-Fan-Personal-Smoke-USB-Rechargeable-Remove-99-97/PRD2K8LG41B00JW">something like this</a>. Might need to get a battery pack separately. Avoid ionizers.</p><p>Any other recommendations?</p><p><strong>6. I’m not a doctor and do not give medical advice, but here’s one thing I can say confidently: GET THEM VACCINATED.</strong></p><p>Most of these things should be provided by the govt. That’s not happening soon, so we should do the best we can with what we have.</p><img src="https://medium.com/_/stat?event=post.clientViewed&referrerSource=full_rss&postId=f77883d8fe6d" width="1" height="1" alt=""><hr><p><a href="https://itsairborne.com/ways-to-keep-your-kid-safe-at-school-f77883d8fe6d">Ways To Keep Your Kid Safe at School</a> was originally published in <a href="https://itsairborne.com">It’s Airborne</a> on Medium, where people are continuing the conversation by highlighting and responding to this story.</p>]]></content:encoded>
